True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 4: William Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs.\n    if person.name == \"William Dickinson\":\n        if person.supported_portland_whigs is None:\n            person.supported_portland_whigs = True\n            changed = True\n\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # All students who want to have a long vacation have summer as their favorite season.\n3. Emma's favorite season is summer.\n4. Mia's favorite season is not the same as Emma's.\n5. James wants to have a long vacation.\n\nFrom premise 4, we know Mia's favorite season cannot be summer. Since there are only four seasons, Mia's favorite season must be either Spring, Fall, or Winter.\n\nPremise 5 tells us that James wants to have a long vacation, which means his favorite season is Summer according to premise 2.\n\nSince Emma's favorite season is Summer and James's favorite season is Summer, Mia's favorite season cannot be Summer. Every printed text is analog media.\n3. All streaming services are digital media.\n4. If an object is a hardcover book, then it is printed text.\n5. If 1984 is a streaming service, then 1984 is a hardcover book.\n\nFrom premise 1 and 3, we can deduce that no streaming service can be analog because all streaming services are digital and no digital media are analog. This means that if 1984 were a streaming service, it would be impossible for 1984 to be analog, which contradicts premise 2 (since every printed text is analog).\n\nSince premise 5 states that if 1984 is a streaming service, then it is a hardcover book, and premise 4 states that if an object is a hardcover book, then it is printed text, we need to consider the possibility of 1984 being a streaming service. However, from the previous deduction, we know that 1984 cannot be a streaming service because it would contradict the premises.\n\nTherefore, 1984 cannot be a streaming service. This leaves us with the possibility that 1984 is not a streaming service. If 1984 is not a streaming service, it could be a printed text, but we do not have any information to definitively conclude that 1984 is a printed text. Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    #     {
        "premises": "No digital media are analog.\nEvery printed text is analog media.\nAll streaming services are digital media.\nIf an object is a hardcover book, then it is printed text.\nIf 1984 is a streaming service, then 1984 is a hardcover book.",
        "conclusions": "1984 is not a streaming service.",
        "rationale": "<nl_cot>\nTo determine if the statement \"1984 is not a streaming service\" is true, false, or uncertain, we need to analyze the given premises step by step.\n\n1. **No digital media are analog.**\n   - This means if something is digital media, it cannot be analog media.\n   - Conversely, if something is analog media, it cannot be digital media.\n\n2. **Every printed text is analog media.**\n   - This means all printed texts fall into the category of analog media.\n\n3. **All streaming services are digital media.**\n   - This means all streaming services fall into the category of digital media.\n\n4. **If an object is a hardcover book, then it is printed text.**\n   - This means that being a hardcover book implies the object is a printed text.\n\n5. **If 1984 is a streaming service, then 1984 is a hardcover book.**\n   - This is a conditional statement. All languages within a language family are related to each other.\n4. French and Spanish are both Romance languages.\n5. German is related to Spanish.\n6. Basque is not related to any other language.\n\nFrom premise 4, we know that both French and Spanish are Romance languages. From premise 3, since all languages within a language family are related to each other, and Spanish is a Romance language, any language related to Spanish must also be a Romance language. However, premise 5 states that German is related to Spanish, but German is not a Romance language (since all Romance languages are Indo-European and German is not Indo-European). This does not contradict the fact that Spanish is a Romance language, but it does not provide any information about Basque.\n\nPremise 6 states that Basque is not related to any other language. William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # All languages within a language family are related to each other.\n4. French and Spanish are both Romance languages.\n5. German is related to Spanish.\n6. Basque is not related to any other language.\n\nFrom these premises, we need to determine if German is a Romance language.\n\n- Premise 2 states that Romance languages form a language family.\n- Premise 3 states that all languages within a language family are related to each other.\n- Premise 5 states that German is related to Spanish.\n\nBased on Premises 2 and 3, if Spanish is a Romance language and German is related to Spanish, then German must be a Romance language. Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # From Premise 4, we know all alligators are not domesticated animals. Since all cows are domesticated animals (Premise 3), and Brown Swiss cattle are cows (Premise 1), no Brown Swiss cattle can be alligators. \n\nSince some pets are Brown Swiss cattle (Premise 2), and no Brown Swiss cattle are alligators, it follows that Ted, being an alligator, cannot be a pet.\n\nThus, the conclusion \"Ted is a pet\" is false.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>",

Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # All cows are domesticated animals.\n4. Alligators are not domesticated animals.\n5. Ted is an alligator.\n\nWe need to determine if the statement \"Ted is a pet and Brown Swiss cattle\" is true, false, or uncertain.\n\nLet's break it down:\n\n- From premise 5, we know Ted is an alligator.\n- From premise 4, alligators are not domesticated animals.\n- From premise 3, all cows are domesticated animals. Therefore, no alligators can be cows, and thus no alligators can be Brown Swiss cattle (since all Brown Swiss cattle are cows).\n- Premise 2 states that some pets are Brown Swiss cattle. However, this does not imply that all Brown Swiss cattle are pets, only that there exists at least one Brown Swiss cattle that is a pet.\n- Since Ted is an alligator and alligators are not domesticated animals, Ted cannot be a cow (and therefore cannot be a Brown Swiss cattle, which is a type of cow).\n\nGiven the premises, we can conclude that Ted cannot be a Brown Swiss cattle because he is an alligator and alligators are not cows.\n\nNow, let's consider if Ted can be a pet:\n- We know that some Brown Swiss cattle are pets, but this does not imply that all Brown Swiss cattle are pets.\n- Since Ted is an alligator and alligators are not domesticated animals, and Brown Swiss cattle are cows and all cows are domesticated, Ted cannot be a pet either.\n\nTherefore, based on the premises, the statement \"Ted is a pet and Brown Swiss cattle\" is false.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>",

Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass Hulk:\n    def __init__(self, angry: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.angry = angry  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: The Hulk is a destroyer.\n\n    @property\n    def wakes_up(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: The Hulk wakes up when he is angry.\n        if self.angry is None:\n            return None\n        return self.angry\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # According to Premise 4, all mature stocks are suitable for a retirement fund. \n\nNow, let's consider the conclusion:\n- If KO is a growth stock, then by Premise 1, KO is bought to earn profits from rapid price appreciation.\n- If KO is bought to earn profits from rapid price appreciation, then by Premise 2, it is not suitable for a retirement fund.\n\nHowever, since KO is a mature stock, it is suitable for a retirement fund. This creates a contradiction because a mature stock cannot be both suitable for a retirement fund and not suitable for a retirement fund.\n\nSince KO is a mature stock, it cannot be a growth stock. Therefore, the condition \"KO is a growth stock or bought to earn profits from rapid price appreciation\" cannot be true because KO is not a growth stock.\n\nIf KO is not a growth stock, it is not bought to earn profits from rapid price appreciation. This means the condition \"KO is bought to earn profits from rapid price appreciation\" is false.\n\nSince the condition \"KO is a growth stock or bought to earn profits from rapid price appreciation\" is false, the entire statement \"If KO is a growth stock or bought to earn profits from rapid price appreciation, then KO is neither a stock nor is its price volatile\" is vacuously true. A statement of the form \"If P, then Q\" is true if P is false, regardless of the truth value of Q.\n\nThus, the statement is true.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # If dried Thai chilies are not baked sweets, then they do not fall under the category of products that cannot be spicy (i.e., cupcakes from Baked by Melissa). Therefore, dried Thai chilies could be mala hotpots or spicy.\n\nGiven that all mala hotpots are spicy, if dried Thai chilies are not baked sweets, they could be mala hotpots. However, we cannot definitively conclude that dried Thai chilies are a mala hotpot just from the given premises. They could also be spicy but not mala hotpots.\n\nTherefore, the statement \"Dried Thai chilies are a mala hotpot\" is uncertain.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (C).\n</answer>",

        "conclusions": "The Hamden Plaza Subway store provides take-out service or does not receive many negative reviews.",
        "rationale": "<nl_cot>\nTo determine if the statement \"The Hamden Plaza Subway store provides take-out service or does not receive many negative reviews\" is true, false, or uncertain, we need to analyze the given premises step by step.\n\n1. **Premise 1**: If a restaurant is listed in Yelp\u2019s recommendations, then the restaurant has not received many negative reviews.\n2. **Premise 2**: All restaurants with a rating greater than four are listed in Yelp\u2019s recommendations.\n3. **Premise 3**: Some restaurants that do not provide take-out service receive many negative reviews.\n4. **Premise 4**: All restaurants that are popular among local residents have ratings greater than four.\n5. **Premise 5**: The Hamden Plaza Subway store has a rating greater than four, or it is popular among local residents.\n\nFrom Premise 5, we know that the Hamden Plaza Subway store either has a rating greater than four or it is popular among local residents (or both).\n\nLet's consider the two cases separately:\n\n**Case 1**: The Hamden Plaza Subway store has a rating greater than four.\n- From Premise 2, since it has a rating greater than four, it is listed in Yelp\u2019s recommendations.\n- From Premise 1, if it is listed in Yelp\u2019s recommendations, it has not received many negative reviews.\n- Therefore, in this case, the store does not receive many negative reviews.\n\n**Case 2**: The Hamden Plaza Subway store is popular among local residents.\n- From Premise 4, since it is popular among local residents, it has a rating greater than four.\n- This case is already covered by Case 1, so we know it does not receive many negative reviews.\n\n**Case 3**: The Hamden Plaza Subway store does not have a rating greater than four and is not popular among local residents.\n- This case is not possible because Premise 5 states that the store has a rating greater than four, or it is popular among local residents.\n\nFrom the analysis, we can conclude that the Hamden Plaza Subway store either does not receive many negative reviews (if it has a rating greater than four) or it does not receive many negative reviews (if it is popular among local residents).\n\nTherefore, the statement \"The Hamden Plaza Subway store provides take-out service or does not receive many negative reviews\" is true because the first part of the statement \"The Hamden Plaza Subway store provides take-out service\" is not directly supported by the premises, but the second part \"does not receive many negative reviews\" is supported by the premises.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

Premise: The Hulk wakes up when he is angry.\n        if self.angry is None:\n            return None\n        return self.angry\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # The Hamden Plaza Subway store has a rating greater than four, or it is popular among local residents.\n\nFrom premise 2 and 5, we can conclude:\n- If the Hamden Plaza Subway store is not popular among local residents, then it must have a rating greater than four (since it has one of the two conditions).\n\nLet's consider the two cases for the Hamden Plaza Subway store:\n\n**Case 1:** The Hamden Plaza Subway store has a rating greater than four.\n- From premise 2, if the Hamden Plaza Subway store has a rating greater than four, it is listed in Yelp's recommendations.\n- From premise 1, if the Hamden Plaza Subway store is listed in Yelp's recommendations, it has not received many negative reviews.\n- From premise 3, some restaurants that do not provide take-out service receive many negative reviews. Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Premise 4: William Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs.\n    if person.name == \"William Dickinson\":\n        if person.supported_portland_whigs is None:\n            person.supported_portland_whigs = True\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # All animals with backbones reproduce by male-and-female mating.\n3. All vertebrate animals have a backbone.\n4. All bees do not reproduce by male-and-female mating.\n5. All queen bees are bees.\n6. Harry is a bee.\n\nFrom premises 2 and 3, we can infer that any animal with a backbone is a vertebrate. \n\nFrom premise 4, we know that all bees do not reproduce by male-and-female mating. This means that bees do not have a backbone, as animals with backbones do.\n\nCombining premises 1, 4, and 6, we can deduce that since Harry is a bee and bees do not have a backbone, Harry cannot be a vertebrate. Therefore, Harry must be an invertebrate.\n\nPremise 5 states that all queen bees are bees. Since Harry is a bee (premise 6), and all bees include queen bees, it is possible that Harry could be a queen bee.\n\nThus, Harry is either an invertebrate or a queen bee.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # This implies that Harry cannot be both a vertebrate and an animal with a backbone. \n\nIf Harry is neither a vertebrate nor an animal with a backbone, he must be an invertebrate (since animals are either invertebrates or vertebrates, and he is not a vertebrate).\n\nSince all bees are not invertebrates (they are either vertebrates or animals with a backbone, but not both), and Harry is a bee, Harry cannot be an invertebrate if he is a bee. Therefore, if Harry is neither a vertebrate nor an animal with a backbone, he cannot be a bee, and thus cannot be a queen bee (since all queen bees are bees).\n\nThus, the conclusion logically follows from the premises.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",
