True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 4: William Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs.\n    if person.name == \"William Dickinson\":\n        if person.supported_portland_whigs is None:\n            person.supported_portland_whigs = True\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Premise: The Hulk wakes up when he is angry.\n        if self.angry is None:\n            return None\n        return self.angry\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 3: The University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom.\n    if person.university is not None and person.university.name == \"University of Edinburgh\":\n        if person.university.location != \"UK\":\n            person.university.location = \"UK\"\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: William Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs.\n    if person.name == \"William Dickinson\":\n        if person.supported_portland_whigs is None:\n            person.supported_portland_whigs = True\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Conclusion: William Dickinson went to schools located in the UK for both high school and university.\n    if person.high_school is None or person.university is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    hs_loc = person.high_school.location\n    uni_loc = person.university.location\n    if hs_loc is None or uni_loc is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if hs_loc == \"UK\" and uni_loc == \"UK\":\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    person = Person(\n        name=\"William Dickinson\",\n        is_british=None,\n        high_school=None,\n        university=None,\n        sat_in_house=None,\n        supported_portland_whigs=None\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(person)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: William Dickinson went to schools located in the UK for both high school and university?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (C).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 3>\n\n\nThe following is the problem you need to solve.\n\n<premises>\nIf a film is appropriate for people of all ages, then children can watch it without guidance from parents.\nIf a film contains excessive erotic and violent content, children cannot watch it without guidance from their parents.\nIf a film is rated General Audience, then it is appropriate for people of all ages.\nAll family-friendly animated films are rated General Audience.\nAll movies in the Frozen series are family-friendly animated films.\n\u201cHachi: A dog\u2019s Tale\u201d is a film.\n\u201cHachi: A dog\u2019s Tale\u201d  is either a family-friendly animated film or is appropriate for people of all ages. \n</premises>\n<conclusion>\n\"Hachi: A dog's Tale\" is rated General Audience.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? \"Hachi: A dog's Tale\" is rated General Audience.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>"

The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    #         "premises": "Everyone who can register to vote in the United States can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\nIf someone has United States citizenship, then they can register to vote in the United States.\nA person either has United States citizenship or Taiwanese citizenship.\nNo Russian Federation officials hold Taiwanese citizenship. \nVladimir neither holds Taiwanese citizenship nor is he a manager at Gazprom. \nEkaterina she can register to vote in the United States, or she is a Russian federation official.",

        "rationale": "<nl_cot>\nLet's analyze the premises step by step:\n\n1. Everyone who can register to vote in the United States can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\n2. If someone has United States citizenship, then they can register to vote in the United States.\n3. A person either has United States citizenship or Taiwanese citizenship.\n4. No Russian Federation officials hold Taiwanese citizenship.\n5. Vladimir neither holds Taiwanese citizenship nor is he a manager at Gazprom.\n6. Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States, or she is a Russian federation official.\n\nFrom premise 5, we know:\n- Vladimir does not hold Taiwanese citizenship.\n- Vladimir is not a manager at Gazprom.\n\nSince Vladimir does not hold Taiwanese citizenship, from premise 3, he must have United States citizenship.\n\nFrom premise 2, if someone has United States citizenship, then they can register to vote in the United States. Therefore, Vladimir can register to vote in the United States.\n\nFrom premise 6, since Vladimir can register to vote in the United States, he fits the condition \"Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States, or she is a Russian federation official.\" However, this premise does not provide additional information about Vladimir being a Russian federation official.\n\nFrom premise 4, we know that no Russian Federation officials hold Taiwanese citizenship. Since Vladimir does not hold Taiwanese citizenship, he cannot be a Russian Federation official.\n\nTherefore, the only conclusion we can draw from the premises is that Vladimir is not a Russian Federation official.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>",

Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     #         "rationale": "<nl_cot>\nLet's break down the premises and see what we can infer step by step.\n\n1. **Premise 1:** Everyone who can register to vote in the United States can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\n2. **Premise 2:** If someone has United States citizenship, then they can register to vote in the United States.\n3. **Premise 3:** A person either has United States citizenship or Taiwanese citizenship.\n4. **Premise 4:** No Russian Federation officials hold Taiwanese citizenship.\n5. **Premise 5:** Vladimir neither holds Taiwanese citizenship nor is he a manager at Gazprom.\n6. **Premise 6:** Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States, or she is a Russian federation official.\n\nWe need to determine whether the conclusion is true, false, or uncertain.\n\nFirst, let's consider Ekaterina:\n- From Premise 6, if Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States, then she can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election (by Premise 1).\n- If Ekaterina cannot register to vote in the United States, then she must be a Russian federation official (since she cannot be a Russian federation official, she must be able to register to vote in the United States).\n\nNext, let's consider Vladimir:\n- From Premise 5, Vladimir neither holds Taiwanese citizenship nor is he a manager at Gazprom.\n\nNow, let's combine these:\n- If Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States, she can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\n- If Ekaterina cannot register to vote in the United States, she must be a Russian federation official.\n- If Ekaterina is a Russian federation official, we do not have any additional information about her participation in the election.\n- Since Vladimir is neither a Russian federation official nor a manager at Gazprom, the statement \"Vladimir is a manager at Gazprom\" is false.\n\nTherefore, the statement \"Ekaterina can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election or Vladimir is a manager at Gazprom\" is true because if Ekaterina is a Russian federation official, the first part of the disjunction is true, and if she is not, the second part is true (since Vladimir is not a manager at Gazprom, the statement is still true).\n\nThe conclusion follows logically from the premises.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? This implies that Vladimir must have United States citizenship (since he cannot have Taiwanese citizenship).\n\nFrom Premise 3, if Vladimir has United States citizenship, he can register to vote in the United States (by Premise 2). Therefore, if Vladimir can register to vote in the United States, he can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election (by Premise 1).\n\nNow, we need to determine the truth of the statement: \"It is not true that Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States and Vladimir can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\"\n\n- If Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States, then by Premise 1, she can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\n- If Vladimir can register to vote in the United States, then by Premise 1, he can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\n\nSince both Ekaterina and Vladimir can register to vote in the United States, both can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election.\n\nTherefore, the statement \"It is not true that Ekaterina can register to vote in the United States and Vladimir can participate in the 2024 United States presidential election\" is false.\n\nThus, the conclusion is that the statement is false.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>",

William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 3: The University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom.\n    if person.university is not None and person.university.name == \"University of Edinburgh\":\n        if person.university.location != \"UK\":\n            person.university.location = \"UK\"\n            changed = True\n\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # All organic compounds are chemical compounds.\n4. All organic compounds contain carbon.\n5. No chemical compounds contain only one element.\n6. The mixture either both is a chemical compound and contains only one element, or neither.\n\nLet's analyze the mixture based on these premises:\n\n- If the mixture is a chemical compound, it cannot contain only one element (from premise 5).\n- The mixture cannot be both a chemical compound and contain only one element (since it contradicts the first part of premise 6).\n- Therefore, the mixture cannot be a chemical compound (since it cannot be both a chemical compound and not a chemical compound simultaneously).\n- If the mixture is not a chemical compound, then it cannot be an organic compound (since all organic compounds are chemical compounds, premise 3).\n- If the mixture is not an organic compound, then it cannot be a hydrocarbon (since all hydrocarbons are organic compounds, premise 1).\n- If the mixture is not a hydrocarbon, then it cannot be an alkane (since all alkanes are hydrocarbons, premise 2).\n\nSince the mixture cannot be any of the above categories (chemical compound, organic compound, hydrocarbon, or alkane), we have no direct information about whether the mixture contains carbon or not based on the given premises. \n\nTherefore, the conclusion that the mixture contains carbon is uncertain.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (C).\n</answer>",

Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # All organic compounds are chemical compounds.\n4. All organic compounds contain carbon.\n5. No chemical compounds contain only one element.\n6. The mixture either both is a chemical compound and contains only one element, or neither.\n\nLet's analyze the conclusion:\n\"If the mixture contains only one element or contains carbon, then the mixture is neither a chemical compound nor an alkane.\"\n\nFrom Premise 5, we know that no chemical compound can contain only one element. This means that if the mixture contains only one element, it cannot be a chemical compound.\n\nFrom Premise 4, we know that all organic compounds contain carbon. Therefore, if the mixture contains carbon, it is an organic compound (and thus a chemical compound).\n\nHowever, the conclusion states that the mixture is \"neither a chemical compound nor an alkane.\" This means that if the mixture contains carbon, it cannot be a chemical compound, which contradicts Premise 4. Similarly, if the mixture contains only one element, it cannot be a chemical compound, which contradicts Premise 5.\n\nGiven these contradictions, the conclusion does not logically follow from the premises.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>",

Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 3: The University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom.\n    if person.university is not None and person.university.name == \"University of Edinburgh\":\n        if person.university.location != \"UK\":\n            person.university.location = \"UK\"\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: William Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs.\n    if person.name == \"William Dickinson\":\n        if person.supported_portland_whigs is None:\n            person.supported_portland_whigs = True\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Conclusion: William Dickinson went to schools located in the UK for both high school and university.\n    if person.high_school is None or person.university is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    hs_loc = person.high_school.location\n    uni_loc = person.university.location\n    if hs_loc is None or uni_loc is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if hs_loc == \"UK\" and uni_loc == \"UK\":\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    person = Person(\n        name=\"William Dickinson\",\n        is_british=None,\n        high_school=None,\n        university=None,\n        sat_in_house=None,\n        supported_portland_whigs=None\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(person)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: William Dickinson went to schools located in the UK for both high school and university?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (C).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 3>\n\n\nThe following is the problem you need to solve.\n\n<premises>\nAll hydrocarbons are organic compounds .\nAll alkanes are hydrocarbons\nAll organic compounds are chemical compounds.\nAll organic compounds contain carbon.\nNo chemical compounds contain only one element.\nThe mixture either both is a chemical compound and contains only one element, or neither. \n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nIf the mixture contains only one element or contains carbon, then the mixture is neither a chemical compound nor an alkane.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # None of the students who currently work in the library are from the computer science department.\n2. All of the students with part-time jobs offered by the university currently work in the library.\n3. All of the students who are taking the database course are from the computer science department.\n4. All of the students taking a class with Professor David are taking the database course.\n5. All students working in the lab are taking a class with Professor David.\n6. James is a student working in the lab.\n7. James doesn't work in the lab or have a part-time job offered by the university.\n\nFrom premise 5 and 6, we can conclude that all students working in the lab are taking a class with Professor David, and since all students taking a class with Professor David are taking the database course (premise 4), James must be taking the database course. \n\nFrom premise 3, since James is taking the database course, he must be from the computer science department.\n\nFrom premise 1, since James is from the computer science department and works in the library (from premise 6), he cannot be one of the students who currently work in the library. Therefore, James does not have a part-time job offered by the university (since all such students work in the library, premise 2).\n\nPremise 7 states that James doesn't work in the lab or have a part-time job offered by the university. Since we have already established that James does not have a part-time job offered by the university, this premise is consistent with our deductions.\n\nTherefore, the statement \"James does not have a part-time job offered by the university\" is true.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain?         "conclusions": "James takes the database course.",
        "rationale": "<nl_cot>\nLet's analyze the premises step by step:\n\n1. **Premise 1**: None of the students who currently work in the library are from the computer science department.\n   - This means if a student works in the library, they are not from the computer science department.\n\n2. **Premise 2**: All of the students with part-time jobs offered by the university currently work in the library.\n   - This means students with such jobs are in the library.\n\n3. **Premise 3**: All of the students who are taking the database course are from the computer science department.\n   - This means if a student is taking the database course, they are from the computer science department.\n\n4. **Premise 4**: All of the students taking a class with Professor David are taking the database course.\n   - This means if a student is taking a class with Professor David, they are taking the database course.\n\n5. **Premise 5**: All students working in the lab are taking a class with Professor David.\n   - This means if a student works in the lab, they are taking a class with Professor David.\n\n6. **Premise 6**: James is a student working in the lab.\n   - Therefore, James is taking a class with Professor David (from Premise 5).\n\n7. **Premise 7**: James doesn't work in the lab or have a part-time job offered by the university.\n   - This means James does not work in the library (since he doesn't work in the lab and part-time jobs in the library are the only jobs that would place him there).\n\nCombining the above, we know:\n- James works in the lab (Premise 6).\n- James is taking a class with Professor David (Premise 6 and 5).\n- Since all students taking a class with Professor David are taking the database course (Premise 4), James must be taking the database course.\n\nTherefore, the conclusion is that James takes the database course.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

Premise: The Hulk wakes up when he is angry.\n        if self.angry is None:\n            return None\n        return self.angry\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # If George can compose and wants to compose, he will compose.\n\nWe need to determine if the statement \"If George will not compose, George can not compose\" is true, false, or uncertain.\n\nLet's break down the premises and see if they support the conclusion.\n\nFrom premise 3, we have:\n\\[ \\text{If George can compose and wants to compose, then George will compose.} \\]\nThis can be written as:\n\\[ \\text{Can compose} \\land \\text{Wants to compose} \\implies \\text{Will compose} \\]\n\nTo derive the conclusion, we need to check the contrapositive of the statement \"If George will not compose, George can not compose\":\n\\[ \\text{Will not compose} \\implies \\text{Can not compose} \\]\n\nThe contrapositive of this statement is:\n\\[ \\text{Can compose} \\implies \\text{Will compose} \\]\n\nThis is the same as premise 3, which is given as a true statement. Therefore, the contrapositive is also true.\n\nThus, if George will not compose, it must be that George can not compose, because if he could compose and wanted to compose, he would have composed, contradicting the fact that he will not compose.\n\nTherefore, the statement \"If George will not compose, George can not compose\" is true.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

This means that the show mentioned in Premise 1 (which gives out roses at 8 pm on Monday) is an episode of The Bachelor.\n\nFrom Premise 3, we know that The Bachelor portrays the lives of real people.\n\nFrom Premise 4, since The Bachelor portrays the lives of real people, it must be a reality TV show.\n\nFrom Premise 6, we know that Breaking Bad is not a reality TV show.\n\nSince the show that gives out roses on TV is an episode of The Bachelor (from Premise 2), and The Bachelor is a reality TV show (from Premise 4), it follows that the show giving out roses on TV is a reality TV show. Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Since bile duct cancer is a deadly disease and comes with a low survival rate, this means colorectal cancer cannot be a bile duct cancer.\n- Therefore, colorectal cancer cannot be a form of Cholangiocarcinoma either, because Cholangiocarcinoma is a subset of bile duct cancer.\n\nGiven the above analysis, if colorectal cancer is a kind of bile duct cancer or a form of Cholangiocarcinoma, it would contradict the fact that colorectal cancer is not both a bile duct cancer and with a low survival rate. Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? regularly are very conscious about their health and eating habits.\n2. **Premise 2**: All people who grew up in health-conscious childhood homes eat salads regularly.\n3. **Premise 3**: All people who fulfill their daily nutritional intakes grew up in health-conscious childhood homes.\n4. **Premise 4**: All people who disregard their physical well-being are not very conscious about their health and eating habits.\n5. **Premise 5**: If people visit the gym at least once a day, then they always fulfill their daily nutritional intakes.\n6. **Premise 6**: Taylor either grew up in a health-conscious childhood home and disregard her physical well-being, or she did neither.\n\nFrom these premises, we need to determine if Taylor neither grew up in a health-conscious childhood home nor visits the gym at least once a day.\n\nLet's break it down:\n- If Taylor grew up in a health-conscious childhood home, then she eats salads regularly (Premise 2).\n- If she eats salads regularly, she is very conscious about her health and eating habits (Premise 1).\n- If she is very conscious about her health and eating habits, she does not disregard her physical well-being (Premise 4).\n\nSo, if Taylor grew up in a health-conscious childhood home, she would not disregard her physical well-being.\n\n- If Taylor does not grow up in a health-conscious childhood home, then she does not eat salads regularly (Premise 2).\n- If she does not eat salads regularly, she is not very conscious about her health and eating habits (Premise 1).\n- If she is not very conscious about her health and eating habits, she could be disregarding her physical well-being (Premise 4).\n\nNow, let's consider the second part of Premise 6:\n- If Taylor grew up in a health-conscious childhood home and disregards her physical well-being, then she would not fulfill her daily nutritional intakes (Premise 3).\n- If she does not fulfill her daily nutritional intakes, she does not visit the gym at least once a day (Premise 5).\n\nCombining these, we see that if Taylor grew up in a health-conscious childhood home, she would not visit the gym at least once a day.\n\nOn the other hand, if Taylor did not grow up in a health-conscious childhood home, she could either be very conscious about her health and eating habits (if she eats salads regularly) or not very conscious about her health and eating habits (if she does not eat salads regularly). If she is not very conscious, she could be disregarding her physical well-being and not fulfilling her daily nutritional intakes, which means she would not visit the gym at least once a day.\n\nTherefore, based on the premises, Taylor could be in either of two states:\n1. She did not grow up in a health-conscious childhood home and does not visit the gym at least once a day.\n\nSince the conclusion states that Taylor neither grew up in a health-conscious childhood home nor visits the gym at least once a day, and given the premises, this conclusion is not necessarily true.
