If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass Hulk:\n    def __init__(self, angry: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.angry = angry  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: The Hulk is a destroyer.\n\n    @property\n    def wakes_up(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: The Hulk wakes up when he is angry.\n        if self.angry is None:\n            return None\n        return self.angry\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 2: William Dickinson attended Westminster School for high school and then the University of Edinburgh.\n    if person.name == \"William Dickinson\":\n        if person.high_school is None:\n            person.high_school = School(\"Westminster School\", location=None)\n            changed = True\n        if person.university is None:\n            person.university = University(\"University of Edinburgh\", location=None)\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: The University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom.\n    if person.university is not None and person.university.name == \"University of Edinburgh\":\n        if person.university.location != \"UK\":\n            person.university.location = \"UK\"\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: William Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs.\n    if person.name == \"William Dickinson\":\n        if person.supported_portland_whigs is None:\n            person.supported_portland_whigs = True\n            changed = True\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Conclusion: William Dickinson went to schools located in the UK for both high school and university.\n    if person.high_school is None or person.university is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    hs_loc = person.high_school.location\n    uni_loc = person.university.location\n    if hs_loc is None or uni_loc is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if hs_loc == \"UK\" and uni_loc == \"UK\":\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    person = Person(\n        name=\"William Dickinson\",\n        is_british=None,\n        high_school=None,\n        university=None,\n        sat_in_house=None,\n        supported_portland_whigs=None\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(person)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: William Dickinson went to schools located in the UK for both high school and university?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (C).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 3>\n\n\nThe following is the problem you need to solve.\n\n<premises>\nThe summer Olympic games is a sporting event. \nThe last summer Olympic games was in Tokyo.\nThe United States won the most medals in Tokyo. \n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe United States won the most medals in the last summer Olympic games.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? No humans have hooves.\n\nThe conclusion we need to evaluate is:\n- Some humans are horses.\n\nLet's analyze the premises:\n- Premise 1 states that all horses have hooves. This means every horse possesses the attribute of having hooves.\n- Premise 2 states that no humans have hooves. This means it is impossible for any human to have hooves.\n\nFrom these premises, we can infer that:\n- If a human were a horse, it would have to have hooves (from Premise 1).\n- However, no human can have hooves (from Premise 2).\n\nTherefore, it is impossible for any human to be a horse. Some grumpy people are mean to animals.\n3. All animal lovers are nice to animals.\n4. All pet owners love animals.\n5. Tom is a pet owner.\n\nFrom premise 3, we know that all animal lovers are nice to animals. From premise 4, since Tom is a pet owner, he loves animals. Therefore, Tom must be nice to animals (since all pet owners love animals, and all animal lovers are nice to animals).\n\nFrom premise 1, we know that if someone is nice to animals, they cannot be mean to animals. Since Tom is nice to animals (from premise 4 and premise 3), Tom cannot be mean to animals.\n\nFrom premise 2, we know that some grumpy people are mean to animals. However, this does not provide any direct information about Tom's personality or behavior towards animals. The statement only tells us about some grumpy people, not all grumpy people.\n\nSince Tom is nice to animals (from premise 4 and premise 3), and no one who is nice to animals is mean to animals (from premise 1), we cannot conclude that Tom is mean to animals. Premise: The Hulk wakes up when he is angry.\n        if self.angry is None:\n            return None\n        return self.angry\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain?         "premises": "No one nice to animals is also mean to animals.\nSome grumpy people are mean to animals.\nAll animal lovers are nice to animals.\nAll pet owners love animals.\nTom is a pet owner.",

        "rationale": "<nl_cot>\nTo determine if the statement \"Tom is not both a grumpy person and mean to animals\" is true, false, or uncertain, we need to analyze the given premises step by step.\n\n1. **Premise 1**: No one nice to animals is also mean to animals.\n   - This can be expressed as: If someone is nice to animals, then they are not mean to animals.\n   - Symbolically: \\( N(x) \\rightarrow \\neg M(x) \\) where \\( N(x) \\) means \"x is nice to animals\" and \\( M(x) \\) means \"x is mean to animals\".\n\n2. **Premise 2**: Some grumpy people are mean to animals.\n   - This means there exists at least one grumpy person who is mean to animals.\n   - Symbolically: \\( \\exists x (G(x) \\land M(x)) \\) where \\( G(x) \\) means \"x is grumpy\".\n\n3. **Premise 3**: All animal lovers are nice to animals.\n   - This means if someone is an animal lover, they are nice to animals.\n   - Symbolically: \\( A(x) \\rightarrow N(x) \\) where \\( A(x) \\) means \"x is an animal lover\".\n\n4. **Premise 4**: All pet owners love animals.\n   - This means if someone is a pet owner, they love animals.\n   - Symbolically: \\( P(x) \\rightarrow A(x) \\) where \\( P(x) \\) means \"x is a pet owner\".\n\n5. **Premise 5**: Tom is a pet owner.\n   - This means Tom is a pet owner.\n   - Symbolically: \\( P(Tom) \\).\n\nFrom Premise 4 and Premise 5, we can infer that Tom is an animal lover:\n\\[ P(Tom) \\rightarrow A(Tom) \\]\n\\[ A(Tom) \\]\n\nFrom Premise 3 and the fact that Tom is an animal lover, we can infer that Tom is nice to animals:\n\\[ A(Tom) \\rightarrow N(Tom) \\]\n\\[ N(Tom) \\]\n\nFrom Premise 1 and the fact that Tom is nice to animals, we can infer that Tom is not mean to animals:\n\\[ N(Tom) \\rightarrow \\neg M(Tom) \\]\n\\[ \\neg M(Tom) \\]\n\nTherefore, Tom cannot be both a grumpy person and mean to animals because:\n- If Tom is a grumpy person (\\( G(Tom) \\)), and some grumpy people are mean to animals, there is no contradiction yet.\n- However, since Tom is nice to animals (\\( N(Tom) \\)), and no one nice to animals is also mean to animals (\\( N(x) \\rightarrow \\neg M(x) \\)), Tom cannot be mean to animals.\n\nThus, Tom cannot be both a grumpy person and mean to animals.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>",

William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Some grumpy people are mean to animals.\n   - This can be written as:\n     \\[\n     \\exists x, (G(x) \\land M(x))\n     \\]\n     where \\( G(x) \\) means \\( x \\) is grumpy.\n\n3. Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass Hulk:\n    def __init__(self, angry: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.angry = angry  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: The Hulk is a destroyer.\n\n    @property\n    def wakes_up(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: The Hulk wakes up when he is angry.\n        if self.angry is None:\n            return None\n        return self.angry\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    #         "rationale": "<nl_cot>\nTo determine whether the statement \"KiKi is a barking dog\" is true, false, or uncertain, we need to analyze the given premises step by step.\n\n1. **Premise Analysis:**\n   - Jane does not like any animals that bark.\n   - All dogs are animals that bark.\n   - Jane likes all animals that jump.\n   - If an animal has legs, then it jumps.\n   - If an animal is terricolous, then it has legs.\n   - KiKi is an animal.\n   - If KiKi neither jumps nor has legs, then KiKi is terricolous or has legs.\n\n2. **Step-by-Step Reasoning:**\n   - From the first premise, we know that if an animal barks, Jane does not like it.\n   - From the second premise, we know that all dogs bark. Therefore, if KiKi is a dog, then KiKi barks.\n   - To determine if KiKi is a dog, we need to use the information about jumping and having legs.\n\n3. **Jumping and Legs:**\n   - From the third premise, Jane likes all animals that jump.\n   - From the fourth premise, if an animal has legs, then it jumps.\n   - From the fifth premise, if an animal is terricolous, then it has legs.\n\n4. **KiKi's Characteristics:**\n   - From the sixth premise, we know KiKi is an animal.\n   - From the seventh premise, if KiKi neither jumps nor has legs, then KiKi is terricolous or has legs.\n     - If KiKi neither jumps nor has legs, then KiKi must be terricolous (since it cannot be both).\n     - If KiKi is terricolous, then according to the fifth premise, KiKi has legs.\n     - If KiKi has legs, then according to the fourth premise, KiKi jumps.\n\n5. **Conclusion:**\n   - If KiKi jumps, then KiKi does not bark (since Jane does not like animals that bark, and she likes animals that jump).\n   - If KiKi has legs, then KiKi jumps, which means KiKi does not bark.\n\nTherefore, based on the premises, KiKi cannot be a barking dog.\n</nl_cot>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>",

Premise: If the Hulk wakes up, then he will break a bridge.\n        if self.wakes_up is None:\n            return None\n        return self.wakes_up\n\nclass Thor:\n    def __init__(self, happy: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.happy = happy  # can be True, False, or None\n\n    @property\n    def is_god(self) -> bool:\n        return True  # Premise: Thor is a god.\n\n    @property\n    def is_destroyer(self) -> bool:\n        # Premise: A god is not a destroyer.\n        return False\n\n    @property\n    def breaks_bridge(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Thor will break a bridge when he is happy.\n        if self.happy is None:\n            return None\n        return self.happy\n\nclass PeterParker:\n    def __init__(self, is_superhero: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_superhero = is_superhero  # True: superhero, False: civilian, None: unknown\n\n    @property\n    def is_civilian(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return not self.is_superhero\n\n    @property\n    def wears_uniform(self) -> Optional[bool]:\n        # Premise: Peter Parker wears a uniform when he is a superhero.\n        if self.is_superhero is None:\n            return None\n        return self.is_superhero\n\ndef apply_premises(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 10: If Thor is happy, then the Hulk is angry.\n    if thor.happy is True and hulk.angry is not True:\n        hulk.angry = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4 is encoded in Hulk.breaks_bridge.\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 1: If one does not reason, then one is not a philosopher.\n    if god.can_reason is False and god.is_philosopher is not False:\n        god.is_philosopher = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # However, we do not have enough information to directly state KiKi is a dog or not a dog based on the given premises. Since having legs implies jumping, and Jane likes all animals that jump, KiKi must jump if it has legs. This means if KiKi does not jump, it cannot have legs. Therefore, if KiKi neither jumps nor has legs, it must be terricolous.\n\n   - If KiKi is terricolous, from the fifth premise, it must have legs. Since Jane likes all animals that jump, KiKi must be something Jane likes if it is terricolous and has legs.\n\n4. **Final Analysis:**\n   - If KiKi neither jumps nor has legs, it must be either terricolous or have legs (from the sixth premise). Therefore, KiKi must jump and have legs if it is terricolous.\n\n   - Since all dogs bark and Jane does not like any animals that bark, KiKi cannot be a dog. William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 9: If a destroyer is breaking a bridge, then Peter Parker is not a civilian,\n    # meaning he must be a superhero.\n    if hulk.is_destroyer and hulk.breaks_bridge is True and peter.is_superhero is not True:\n        peter.is_superhero = True\n        changed = True\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker):\n    while apply_premises(thor, hulk, peter):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(thor: Thor, hulk: Hulk, peter: PeterParker) -> str:\n    run_inference(thor, hulk, peter)\n    if thor.happy is True:\n        if peter.wears_uniform is True:\n            return \"True\"\n        elif peter.wears_uniform is False:\n            return \"False\"\n        else:\n            return \"Uncertain\"\n    else:\n        # If Thor is not happy, the implication is vacuously true.\n        return \"True\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Initial conditions:\n    # Peter Parker is either a superhero or a civilian.\n    # Here we assume initially he is a civilian (is_superhero = False).\n    # The Hulk's anger is initially unknown (set to False for determinism).\n    thor = Thor(happy=True)       # Premise: Thor is happy.\n    hulk = Hulk(angry=False)        # Initial state; will be updated by inference.\n    peter = PeterParker(is_superhero=False)  # Initially a civilian.\n    return check_conclusion(thor, hulk, peter)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: If Thor is happy, then Peter Parker wears a uniform?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (A).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 1>\n\n<EXAMPLE 2>\n<premises>\nAll philosophers reason.\nSome sophists reason.\nAll who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\nNobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is morally perfect.\nThe theistic God is a sophist.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nThe theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n</question>\n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass TheisticGod:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 is_philosopher: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_sophist: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_reason: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 can_distinguish: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 is_morally_perfect: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.is_philosopher = is_philosopher       # Unknown initially\n        self.is_sophist = is_sophist               # Given (Premise 6)\n        self.can_reason = can_reason               # Unknown initially\n        self.can_distinguish = can_distinguish     # Unknown initially\n        self.is_morally_perfect = is_morally_perfect # Given (Premise 5)\n\ndef apply_premises(god: TheisticGod) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 1: All philosophers reason.\n    if god.is_philosopher is True and god.can_reason is not True:\n        god.can_reason = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 3: All who can reason can distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.can_reason is True and god.can_distinguish is not True:\n        god.can_distinguish = True\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 3: If one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood, then one cannot reason.\n    if god.can_distinguish is False and god.can_reason is not False:\n        god.can_reason = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 4: Nobody who can distinguish truth from falsehood is morally perfect.\n    if god.can_distinguish is True and god.is_morally_perfect is not False:\n        god.is_morally_perfect = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Contrapositive of Premise 4: If one is morally perfect, then one cannot distinguish truth from falsehood.\n    if god.is_morally_perfect is True and god.can_distinguish is not False:\n        god.can_distinguish = False\n        changed = True\n\n    # Premise 2: Some sophists reason.\n    # This only tells us that at least one sophist reasons,\n    # so it does not force that all sophists (including God) must reason.\n    # Premises 5 and 6 are given.\n\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(god: TheisticGod):\n    while apply_premises(god):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(god: TheisticGod) -> str:\n    run_inference(god)\n    # Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher.\n    # if is_sophist or is_philosopher is None, then Uncertain\n    if god.is_sophist is None or god.is_philosopher is None:\n        return \"Uncertain\"\n    if god.is_sophist is True and god.is_philosopher is True:\n        return \"True\"\n    else:\n        return \"False\"\n\ndef func():\n    # Premise 5: God is morally perfect -> True\n    # Premise 6: God is a sophist -> True\n    god = TheisticGod(\n        is_philosopher=None,\n        is_sophist=True,\n        can_reason=None,\n        can_distinguish=None,\n        is_morally_perfect=True\n    )\n    return check_conclusion(god)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    result = func()\n    print(\"Conclusion: The theistic God is a sophist and a philosopher?\", result)\n</code>\n<answer>\nThe final answer is (B).\n</answer>\n</EXAMPLE 2>\n\n<EXAMPLE 3>\n<premises>\nWilliam Dickinson was a British politician who sat in the House of Commons William Dickinson attended Westminster school for high school and then the University of Edinburgh. \nThe University of Edinburgh is a university located in the United Kingdom. \nWilliam Dickinson supported the Portland Whigs. \nPeople who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n</premises>\n<conclusion>\nWilliam Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</conclusion>\n<question>\nIs the following statement true, false, or uncertain? William Dickinson went to schools located in the United Kingdom for both high school and university.\n</question> \n<options>\n(A) True\n(B) False\n(C) Uncertain\n</options>\n<code>\nfrom typing import Optional\n\nclass School:\n    def __init__(self, name: str, location: Optional[str] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.location = location\n\nclass University(School):\n    pass\n\nclass Person:\n    def __init__(self,\n                 name: str,\n                 is_british: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 high_school: Optional[School] = None,\n                 university: Optional[School] = None,\n                 sat_in_house: Optional[bool] = None,\n                 supported_portland_whigs: Optional[bool] = None):\n        self.name = name\n        self.is_british = is_british\n        self.high_school = high_school\n        self.university = university\n        self.sat_in_house = sat_in_house\n        self.supported_portland_whigs = supported_portland_whigs\n\ndef apply_premises(person: Person) -> bool:\n    changed = False\n\n    # Premise 5: People who supported the Portland Whigs did not get a seat in the Parliament.\n    # (No update is made here as it does not affect school location.)\n    return changed\n\ndef run_inference(person: Person):\n    while apply_premises(person):\n        pass\n\ndef check_conclusion(person: Person) -> str:\n    run_inference(person)\n    #
